E. Fusion of multiple types of features based on FGN
In DMTT, the feature matrix G(l−1) that is input at layer l contains more detailed information about each node, while the feature matrix Gˆ(l) learned based on DMTT places greater emphasis on the information guided by multi-scale neighbor topology embedding. Therefore, it is necessary to incorporate G(l−1) into the feature learning process at layer l. To integrate the information contained in Gˆ(l) and G(l−1), we establish an FGN (feature gate network) after DMTT at layer l, with the weight matrix denoted as α(l),
α(l) = σ(W gate(l)(Gˆ(l)∥G(l−1)) + bgate(l)), (12)
where W gate(l) and bgate(l) are learnable weight matrices and bias, and σ is the Sigmoid activation function. All parameters of the FGN are randomly initialized and are learnable during the training process, allowing it to discern the more significant features in Gˆ(l) and G(l−1). The FGN-enhanced node feature representation is denoted
as G(l) ∈ RNv×Nv ,
G(l) = α(l) ⊙ Gˆ(l) + (1 − α(l)) ⊙ G(l−1). (13)
When l ̸= L, G(l) will serve as the input for the next layer of DMTT, where l = L, G(L) represents the final node feature representation matrix.


